38. pristina vota novo, ‘ pay an old-world vow with a novel sacrifice.' To make vows for the safe return of husbands was an ancient custon1; to pay them in the form of the sacrifice of a lock of hair was a new thing, at least in Egypt. Ellis renders, ‘ pay the vows of the past with an offering of to-day ' —a frigid antithesis, but perhaps possible in an Alexandrino poet.
